I have advised over 100 FAILED startups and over a dozen successful ones,   All failed startup founders have in common is their obsession with their idea, premium features, market size, news clippings, trends, and many other romanticized vanity figures.    The common denominator of the successful ones is they're all laser-focused on a theorized principle of a problem or current state that can be changed, and they constantly validate their ever-evolving theories with real potentially paying users and only build what's minimally required to get paid.   It is comical when I start a conversation with a founder; if they begin romanticizing ideas or vanity numbers, I'm like, how far in the abis are you? What did you do? Do you have any proof? The response is always some vanity figure and news clippings.   And funny enough, the successful ones will only build for a group of users (or a single high-paying), what's needed and only when needed, and the failures will have already developed and wasted thousands of dollars (in some cases over $1M) on products that no one wants.  I have one advice to all these founders: start selling to users and stop everything else.   One of the questions I get is, how can I sell before I have a product? To that, I ask, how can you build without knowing if a person is willing to pay for it?  The ones I love to work with are the ones trying to speed up the process of validation, fail fast, have a curious mind, have theories and prove/disprove them, find principles, and understand the problem they're trying to solve while delivering a solution to a single user at a time.   Romanticizing vanity numbers and ideas has killed great potential entrepreneurs and wasted millions of dollars.

Jaime executes the framework with adapted Scrum methodology, ensuring he remains agile, iterative, and customer-centric throughout.  Jamie, took the leap with our comprehensive framework. He began his journey from idea to a thriving business, and letting us guide every step of the way.  Without a holistic framework, Jamie risked spending time and money in the wrong areas, potential technology pitfalls, misaligned product development, and missing out on critical market opportunities.  With our framework by his side, Jamie launches a product that resonates with his audience. He stands tall in his industry, his SaaS solution thriving, and his vision realized. My company, a Series A startup, is starting a new product initiative that involves Generative AI.  Even if we are well funded with bigger team, the approach to validate a new idea stays similar to #indiehackers; or at least it should be the same.  ğŸ‘‰ Here is a simple tip for anyone building Generative AI; or heck any product  When it is a new idea/service, the only thing that matters is   "Is this a service that solves a painful problem?"  In the execution, the most important question you should be asking is   "What is the leanest but surest way to validate this?"  By nature, your Generative AI service (or any service) will not be as good as the expert's manually curated / created work.  Examples â€¢ AI photoshoot -> Human photoshopped â€¢ AI Marketing -> Marketing experts â€¢ Translations, Content Suggestions, Tutoring and so on. All the same.  Most of the times, an expert's curated service beats any software.   So, offer a service and be the person to manually do the work for them for the best quality of service.   It may result in delayed time, but often that is a better trade-off than degraded quality of value returned.  If your best quality of service doesn't 'Wow' them and keep them as your customers, your productized software will not work.  You first have to validate if there is demand.  Tech helps with scalability and your first concern should not be scalability.  ==  Yes, as $3M ARR+ Series A, we are launching a new service with manual human labour behind the scenes to test our MVP to validate the demand.  If more advanced and better funded companies are doing so, what is holding you back from being lean and scrappy?

Hey, founder, Why are you feeling low today?    The million-dollar idea does not excite you anymore.    Simple things look like an uphill task. Motivation is at an all-time low:  We all face ups and downs in our start-up journey.    But why? From my real experience, I could think of possible reasons.    Funding: Running low on funds can really impact a business, especially for committed founders. Competition: Standing out in a competitive business landscape can lead to discouragement among startup founders.  Personal Sacrifices: Starting and growing a business often involves personal sacrifices, leading to stress and burnout.  Setbacks: Despite planning, setbacks are inevitable and can be demoralizing for founders.  Burnout: Demanding startup responsibilities can lead to burnout, affecting motivation and well-being.    What to do: Talk to people you connect with.   Your friends, family, or mentors. Do not be tough on yourself.  You have it in you.   Give yourself a little time.  It is a long-haul game.   Your mental well-being comes first.

"Startup Journey: From Idea to Launch in 5 Weeks"  Embark on an interactive, hands-on experience where you not only learn the ins and outs of launching a startup but actually put those learnings into action. This 5-week course is designed for budding entrepreneurs ready to turn their ideas into realities.  Format & Pricing:  Mode: Cohort, Live weekly calls (recorded for those who can't attend). Duration: 5 weeks. Group Size: Limited to 6-8 participants for personalized attention. Investment: $150 - $200 total. Course Breakdown:  Call 1: "Laying the Foundation" Dive into the methodology behind your startup process (literally your twitter thread). Explore the process of ideation and brainstorming. Assignment: Everyone submit their  startup idea on a platform you develop / host (or just google docs).  Call 2: "Pitch Perfect" Participants pitch their startup ideas (60-second limit) and receive real-time feedback and insights from you and participants. Then you teach them to set goals for the coming week, alongside with your own process. Keep objectives achievable.  Call 3: "Gaining Traction" from now it's a peer-group for accountability and support. Showcase the deliverables of your startup, and ask them to show theirs. Call 4: "Maintaining Momentum"Continue with the interactive show-and-tell sessions. Engage in peer group feedback, delve deeper into each startup's journey, and overcome challenges together.  Call 5: "Ready, Set, Launch!"Finalize strategies, business models, and marketing plans. Celebrate the progress of each startup. Discuss next steps and post-course support. Thriving in a Diverse Ecosystem: Canada's multicultural society is reflected in its business landscape, creating an environment where diverse perspectives and ideas flourish. As an entrepreneur, this ecosystem allows you to tap into a rich talent pool, collaborate with people from various backgrounds, and develop products and services that resonate on a global scale.  A Foundation for Innovation: The Start-up Visa Program recognizes that innovation isn't confined to a single sector or industry. Partner with a designated organization that aligns with your vision, and secure a Letter of Support that validates your business idea and enhances your application.  A Bright Future Awaits: Canada's Start-up Visa Program is more than an immigration pathway â€“ it's an opportunity to contribute to a nation known for its innovation, diversity, and resilience. "The Art of War" for Business.  "The Art of War" by Sun Tzu (5th century BCE), is one of the most concise and influential works that provide valuable insights into the principles of warfare, leadership, and conflict resolution. Sun Tzu's ideas have had a lasting impact not only on military thought but also on business, politics, and various other fields.  Applying the principles of "The Art of War" to business strategy can be beneficial for decision-making and competitive advantage. Here are some examples of using the principles in a business context:  â—‡ Know Your Market and Competitors:     â€¢ Understand your industry, competitors, and market trends thoroughly.    â€¢ Gather intelligence to identify strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats (SWOT analysis).  â—‡ Adaptability and Flexibility:     â€¢ Be adaptable and ready to pivot when market conditions change.    â€¢ Adjust your business strategies based on emerging trends and customer preferences.  â—‡ Sun Tzu's Five Factors:     â€¢ Apply the Five Factors (Moral Law, Heaven, Earth, the Commander, and Method and Discipline) to assess your business environment and strategy.  â—‡ Know Your Strengths and Weaknesses:     â€¢ Conduct an internal analysis to identify your organization's strengths and weaknesses.    â€¢ Allocate resources to reinforce strengths and address weaknesses.  â—‡ Deception and Misdirection:     â€¢ Use marketing and branding to create a perception of strength and quality, even if you are a smaller business.    â€¢ Employ tactics that surprise competitors and disrupt their plans.  â—‡ Win Without Fighting:     â€¢ Seek win-win solutions and partnerships in negotiations.    â€¢ Compete through innovation and unique value propositions that make it difficult for competitors to directly challenge you.  â—‡ Strategy and Tactics:     â€¢ Develop a clear overarching business strategy (e.g., cost leadership, differentiation).    â€¢ Implement tactical plans and initiatives that align with your strategy.  â—‡ Resource Management:     â€¢ Efficiently allocate and manage resources, including finances, personnel, and time.    â€¢ Avoid overextension by focusing on key areas of strength and opportunity.  â—‡ The Art of Timing:     â€¢ Identify the right timing for product launches, marketing campaigns, and market entries.    â€¢ Seize opportunities when your competitors are weak or unprepared.  â—‡ Leadership and Decision-Making:     â€¢ Lead with wisdom, adaptability, and a deep understanding of your team's strengths and weaknesses.    â€¢ Make well-informed decisions based on accurate information and analysis.  â—‡ Avoid Protracted Conflicts:     â€¢ Resolve disputes and conflicts swiftly to prevent long-term damage to relationships or resources.    â€¢ Seek peaceful resolutions in negotiations when possible.  â—‡ Gather Intelligence on your Competitors:     â€¢ Gather competitive intelligence to stay informed about your rivals' strategies, weaknesses, and plans.    â€¢ Leverage this information to make informed decisions and anticipate market moves.  â—‡ Balance Risk and Reward:     â€¢ Assess the risks associated with your business decisions and take calculated risks when the potential rewards justify them.  â—‡ Continuous Improvement:     â€¢ Implement a culture of continuous improvement to refine your products, services, and processes.    â€¢ Strive for excellence in all aspects of your business.  â—‡ Winning Hearts and Minds:     â€¢ Build strong customer relationships and brand loyalty through exceptional customer service and quality.    â€¢ Ensure that your customers become advocates for your business.  By incorporating these principles from "The Art of War" into your business strategy, you can enhance your competitive edge, make more informed decisions, and navigate the complexities of the business world more effectively.

Hay Baling Business Idea with a Budget of $25,000 USD in Zimbabwe: Risks and Benefits  Business Idea: Starting a hay baling business involves producing and selling baled hay to farmers, livestock owners, and other agricultural businesses. The business would require equipment such as a hay baler, tractor, rake, and other necessary machinery to efficiently harvest, bale, and store hay.  Budget Allocation: 1. Hay Baler and Equipment: $15,000 2. Second Hand Tractor and Attachments: $6,000 3. Storage Facility/Infrastructure: $2,000 4. Marketing and Promotion: $1,000 5. Miscellaneous Expenses: $1,000  Risks: 1. Weather Conditions: Adverse weather conditions, such as heavy rainfall or drought, can impact hay production and quality, potentially leading to lower yields and financial losses. 2. Market Demand and Competition: The demand for hay may fluctuate due to changes in livestock numbers, feed alternatives, or economic factors. Additionally, competition from existing hay suppliers in the area could affect sales. 3. Equipment Maintenance and Breakdowns: Machinery breakdowns or maintenance issues can disrupt operations and result in additional expenses and downtime. 4. Price Volatility: Hay prices can vary depending on supply and demand factors. Fluctuations in prices may affect profitability. 5. Seasonal Nature of Business: Hay production is seasonal, typically during the growing season. This means generating revenue during other times of the year may be challenging.  Benefits: 1. Revenue Potential: The hay industry can be profitable, especially in areas with a high demand for livestock feed. Selling baled hay can provide a steady income stream. Matebeleland areas.  2. Diversification: The business can provide diversification for farmers or individuals with existing agricultural operations, allowing them to expand their product offerings and income streams. 3. Utilization of Resources: Utilizing available land and resources to grow and sell hay can maximize the productivity and profitability of the agricultural enterprise. 4. Market Stability: The need for hay remains relatively stable, as livestock owners, equestrian centers, and other agricultural businesses rely on it for animal feed. 5. Long-Term Resilience: Building a reputation for producing high-quality hay and establishing strong relationships with customers can lead to long-term business stability and growth.  Risk Mitigation Strategies: 1. Diversify Customer Base: Target a diverse range of customers, to reduce dependence on a single market segment. 2. Monitor Market Trends: Stay informed about market trends, livestock numbers, and feed alternatives to anticipate changes in demand and adjust production accordingly. 3. Implement Maintenance Schedule: Regularly maintain and service equipment to minimize breakdowns and unexpected repairs. Consider investing in backup machinery or establishing relationships with equipment repair services. 4. Develop Storage and Preservation Plan: Properly store and preserve baled hay to maintain quality and prevent spoilage, ensuring a reliable supply for customers. 5. Financial Planning: Maintain a financial cushion to withstand potential market fluctuations and unexpected expenses. Consider diversifying income sources or exploring value-added products like hay pellets or haylage to mitigate risks.
